Forecasting - SES and Exponential Smoothing¶

This notebook demonstrates how to forecast time series using Simple Exponential Smoothing (SES) and the more general Exponential Smoothing methods. This notebook builds off the concepts introduced last week which forecasted using the MEAN and Naive methods. These two fundamental approaches weight historical data. The MEAN method assumes all data are equally important, while the Naive method considers the most recent observation as the only data point that matters. The SES method automates weighting the historical data for you. The SES method however can be limiting because it is only appropriate there is no trend and no seasonality in the time series. The more general Exponential Smoothing methods overcome these limitations.

This notebook uses the US Retail Employment data set introduced last week.

Simple Forecasting¶

As a quick review, the two simplest forecasting methods are:

  • Average all historical measurements - all future forecasts equal the AVERAGE
  • Use the most recent (last) observation as the forecast -> Naive method

The average or MEAN method is easy to calculate...

In [24]:
train_series.mean()
Out[24]:
14623.75277777778

The most recent or last observation is the Naive forecaster:

In [25]:
train_series.iloc[ -1 ]
Out[25]:
16394.3

Make these simple forecasts on the hold out test set.

Let's compile everything into a Pandas DataFrame.

The simple MEAN and Naive methods are the building blocks for all other forecasting strategies. Last week, we also discussed the SEASONAL NAIVE method and an approach that combines the STL decomposition with a simple Naive forecastor. Those two methods will not be repeated here, but please recall that the SEASONAL NAIVE method was the BEST out of the 4 models on the hold out test set.

Time Series Forecasting Methods¶

All "more advanced" forecasters build on the previously illustrated methods. The "more advanced" approaches try to "blend" aspects of the historical average, the most recent measurement, and seasonal behavior.

The average method treats ALL historical measurements as EQUALLY important. Whereas the Naive method treats only the most recent measurement as being important. Seasonal Naive treats the last year's seasonal measurement as the most important.

Simple Exponential Smoothing (SES)¶

SES "blends" the Average and Naive methods together to find the "optimal" weight to apply to the historical data.

In [32]:
from statsmodels.tsa.api import SimpleExpSmoothing
In [33]:
train_ses_model = SimpleExpSmoothing( train_series, initialization_method='estimated' )
In [34]:
train_ses_model_fit = train_ses_model.fit(optimized=True)

However, why would SES convert to the Naive forecastor? The SES is best suited when there is NO trend AND there is NO seasonal pattern! This data set clearly has both! Thus, the SES method is not well suited to this application, but it is still useful to fit because it will serve as a benchmark for more advanced methods.

Exponential Smoothing¶

We can include trends and seasonal patterns to improve the model. These more general approaches are referred to as Exponential Smoothing models. However, Exponential Smoothing models are given specific names based on the types of components/patterns they can handle.

The Holt method is SES with TRENDS.

The Holt-Winters method is SES with TRENDS and SEASONS.

In [43]:
from statsmodels.tsa.api import ExponentialSmoothing

We know this data has a Seasonal component and a Trend. So let's jump straight to the Holt-Winters method instead of first examining the Holt Method. You must specify the seasonal_periods argument when initializing the ExponentialSmoothing() function. Monthly data has 12 seasonal periods in a year. Quarterly data has 4 seasonal periods in a year. The TREND is included by setting trend='add' and the SEASON component is included by setting seasonal='add'. If we only specified trend='add' and did not set seasonal the we would fit a Holt model instead of Holt-Winters.

In [44]:
train_hw_model = ExponentialSmoothing(train_series, seasonal_periods=12, 
                                      trend='add', seasonal='add', 
                                      initialization_method='estimated')

Apply the .fit() method to fit the model.

In [45]:
train_hw_model_fit = train_hw_model.fit()

The Holt-Winters model has many more coefficients compared to the SES model.

Model Selection¶

Hold Out Test Set¶

We can see from the previous figures that the Holt-Winters method is the BEST model. The hold out TEST SET forecasts are very close to the observations. However, we can quantify the performance using a performance metric as discussed last week. For example, we can calculate the hold-out TEST SET RMSE and identify the BEST model as the model with the LOWEST hold out TEST SET RMSE.

The MEAN or AVERAGE method's hold out TEST SET RMSE is:

In [49]:
np.sqrt( ( ( my_forecasts.observed - my_forecasts.AVERAGE )**2 ).mean() )
Out[49]:
1190.6051791210214

The Naive method's hold out TEST SET RMSE is:

In [50]:
np.sqrt( ( ( my_forecasts.observed - my_forecasts.Naive )**2 ).mean() )
Out[50]:
632.3527036537291

The SES method's hold out TEST SET RMSE is essentially the same value as the Naive method. That is because the SES model essentially turned into the Naive method.

In [51]:
np.sqrt( ( ( test_series - ses_forecast )**2 ).mean() )
Out[51]:
631.7102460279998

The Holt-Winters method's hold out TEST SET RMSE is the smallest of these 4 models. As a reminder, last week the Seasonal Naive method had a hold-out TEST SET RMSE of roughly 82. Thus, the Holt-Winters method is even better than the Seasonal Naive method from last week! The Holt-Winters method is capable of capturing patterns that we saw with manually accounting for the Seasonal patterns!

In [52]:
np.sqrt( ( ( test_series - hw_forecast )**2 ).mean() )
Out[52]:
40.61716823186939

AIC/BIC¶

The statsmodels objects .summary() methods displayed information very similar to the information associated with Linear Models. The Exponential Smoothing forecasting family uses a Gaussian Likelihood just like Linear Models. Many forecasting methods have the exact same assumptions as Linear Models!

AIC and BIC require a Likelihood, and the Exponential Smoothing forecasting family includes a Likelihood. Thus, AIC and BIC can be calculated for SES and Exponential Smoothing forecastors! This provides another way to select the BEST model without having to split the data into training and test sets! The .aic and .bic attributes from the statsmodels objects can be used to extract the AIC and BIC for the models.

In [53]:
ic_results = pd.DataFrame({'model': ['SES', 'Holt-Winters'],
                           'AIC': [train_ses_model_fit.aic, train_hw_model_fit.aic],
                           'BIC': [train_ses_model_fit.bic, train_hw_model_fit.bic]})

Lower values of AIC/BIC are considered better. Thus, even though Holt-Winters has more unknown parameters to estimate compared to SES, the added complexity is worth it according AIC and BIC. Both AIC and BIC are therefore consistent with the hold-out TEST SET model selection.

In [54]:
ic_results
Out[54]:
model AIC BIC
0 SES 3553.490246 3561.051733
1 Holt-Winters 2394.122231 2454.614127

More recent statsmodels versions also include the AICc metric which stands for the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) with small sample correction. This is the Information Criterion metric favored by the Rob Hyndman in the Forecasting: Principles and Practice book. It is less conservative than AIC, but not as conservative as BIC.

In [55]:
ic_results['AICc'] = [train_ses_model_fit.aicc, train_hw_model_fit.aicc]

It does not matter for this example though. The Holt-Winters method is clearly better than the SES model in this application.

In [56]:
ic_results
Out[56]:
model AIC BIC AICc
0 SES 3553.490246 3561.051733 3553.615638
1 Holt-Winters 2394.122231 2454.614127 2396.364854

Prediction Uncertainty¶

Another consequence of the fact that the model involves a LIKELIHOOD is that the model can include uncertainty in the predictions. The uncertainty is calculated just like Linear Models because the Likelihood is a Gaussian likelihood! Meaning, we could view the CONFIDENCE INTERVAL and the PREDICTION INTERVAL. The confidence interval is the uncertainty on the average output or trend, while the prediction interval is the uncertainty of a single measurement.

Time series forecasting is not interested in confidence intervals. We only show the PREDICTION INTERVALS for future forecasts in the time series methods! This is because we can only observe the future once. Think back to the 2016 US Presidential election. It does not matter if someone was confident that on average Hillary Clinton would win. The election happened once and only once. The uncertainty in a single observation is what really matters!

Accessing the prediction interval for the SES and Exponential Smoothing (like Holt-Winters) in statsmodels is rather odd...

Unfortunately we need to generate simulated values and then summarize them.

Let's generate 2000 possible future "paths". Behind the scenes 2000 replications or repetitions of possible futures are randomly generated. This is accomplished via the .simulate() method.

In [57]:
hw_sims = train_hw_model_fit.simulate( test_series.size, repetitions=2000, error='add' )

SES and STL¶

Last week, we manually combined a simple forecasting approach with the STL decomposition. This provides for a very flexible modle, but the manual execution was quite tedious. In practice, you do not need to manually create such a model. Instead, a function call exists to combine a simple forecaster like SES with the STL method.

In [70]:
from statsmodels.tsa.forecasting.stl import STLForecast
In [71]:
train_stlf_model_fit = STLForecast( train_series, SimpleExpSmoothing,
                                   model_kwargs={'initialization_method': 'estimated'}).fit()
In [125]:
print( train_stlf_model_fit.summary() )

I recommend comparing the composite model with other approaches with hold out TEST SETS compared with AIC/BIC/AICc due to the fact this method involves two modeling "levels". The hold out TEST SET RMSE for this composite model is given below. The composite model model does not perform as well as the Holt-Winters method in this case.

In [81]:
np.sqrt( ( ( test_series - stlf_forecast )**2 ).mean() )
Out[81]:
100.92149119553984

We essentially manually created this model last week. As a reminder, the manual STL Reseason Naive model had a hold out TEST SET RMSE of about 100. The STLForecast() function is capable of creating the model that we manually made! Thus, you do not need to manually go through the tedious actions from last week. In practice, you can use STLForecast() to create such a model!

Summary¶

This report demonstrated how to use statsmodels to train SES, Exponential Smoothing models such as Holt-Winters, and composite models that combine STL with SES. Making and visualizing forecasts and forecast Prediction Intervals were demonstrated. Lastly, model selection concepts of identifying the best model based on hold-out TEST SETS and Information Criterion metrics including AIC, BIC, and AICc were discussed.
